(10, 8, 8, 2, 0, '65.190.15.53', 1306027683, 0, 1, 1, 1, 1, '', 'Java programming guidelines', 'Java programming guidelines for developers:\n\n\nIndenting\n\n\nDragon Annihilators uses the &quot;BSD KNF style&quot; for indenting. An example:\n\n[code:2v6x524m]    \n                if ($foo == ''bar'') {\n                    something();\n                    elseif ($bar) {\n                        somethingElse();\n                    }\n                }\n                    [/code:2v6x524m] Dealing with warnings\n\n\nDo not write code that is riddled with warnings. Do not write code that suppresses warnings for no reason.\nExample of bad code:\n\n[code:2v6x524m]    \n                    @SuppressWarnings(&quot;rawtypes&quot;)\n                    List darkquest = new ArrayList();\n                        [/code:2v6x524m]\n\n    Warnings that were suppressed:\n    List is a raw type. References to generic type List should be parameterized\n    ArrayList is a raw type. References to generic type ArrayList should be parameterized\n\nExample of good code:\n\n[code:2v6x524m]        \n                    List&lt;String&gt; darkquest = new ArrayList&lt;String&gt;();\n                        [/code:2v6x524m] Dealing with exceptions\n\n\nAll exceptions should be handled. This means do not surround your code with a try {} catch(Exception e) {} and hide exceptions. If your code throws errors, figure out why it does so. Do not catch the error and do nothing with it.\nUsing exceptions VS returning null\n\n    If you are always expecting to find a value then throw the exception if it is missing. The exception would mean that there was a problem.\n    If the value can be missing or present and both are valid for the application logic then return a null.\n\nThe benefits of using exceptions\n\n    Exceptions are more informative. If you throw new Exception(''Argument 1 was null''), the stack trace will include that as the reason. If you return a null, you will only get a NullPointerException\n    Exception checking can be forced. This means if you write a function that may have an error in it, the person who uses your function will be forced by the compiler to handle the error. If you return a null, he might not handle it himself and the application will throw a NullPointerException / crash.\n\n\n\n\nDocumenting\n\n\nAt least all public methods must be documented with Javadoc. The more you document, the better.\nIf you see someone not documenting, notify them. If you see an old function that isn''t documented, document it! We''re here to better the software.\n\n[code:2v6x524m]                        \npackage org&#46;darkquest&#46;gs&#46;model&#46;snapshot;\n\nimport java&#46;util&#46;ArrayList;\n\n\n/**\n * Chat log class, stores chat string, time of message, message owner and set of players that saw the message\n * @author Pets\n *\n */\npublic class Chatlog extends Snapshot {\n\n    /**\n     * The messages that was sent\n     */\n    private String message;\n    /**\n     * Set of players that received the message;\n     */\n    private ArrayList recievers = new ArrayList();\n\n    /**\n     * Constructor\n     * @param sender player that sent the message\n     * @param chatstring the message that was sent\n     * @param recievers players that saw the message\n     *\n     */\n    public Chatlog(String sender, String chatstring, ArrayList recievers) {\n        super(sender);\n        this&#46;message = chatstring;\n        this&#46;recievers = recievers;\n    }\n    /**\n     * @return list of player names that saw the message\n     */\n    public ArrayList getRecievers() {\n        return recievers;\n    }\n    /**\n     * @return the message\n     */\n    public String getMessage() {\n        return message;\n    }\n}[/code:2v6x524m]', 'c99333637071f72e011ebc22717185e7', 0, 'AIA=', '2v6x524m', 1, 0, '', 0, 0, 0, 1, 0, '', 0),
(11, 9, 12, 2, 0, '65.190.15.53', 1306027753, 0, 1, 1, 1, 1, '', 'Alternate exp formula for combat', '[quote=&quot;Latifundio&quot;:co5tec39]What this does:\n\nWith this low lvl mobs will give small exp and the higher lvl is a mob, the better exp it will give.\n\nThe problem with rscd current formula is that you get rewarded for fighting chickens and rats instead of being rewarded when you fight high lvl npc. Also is more fun training at the strongest enemy that oneself can handle.\n[code:co5tec39]public static int combatExperience(Mob mob) {\n    double exp = Math&#46;pow(mob&#46;getCombatLevel(), 2) * 1&#46;5D;\n    return (int) (mob instanceof Player ? (exp / 4D) &#58; exp);\n   }[/code:co5tec39]Note: This goes in Formulae.java and need to replace the old formula. Also exprate need to be set at 1 at Constants.java (and maybe Player.java) or it will give too much exp from lvl 100+ npcs.[/quote:co5tec39]', '0ab97c499da4012ca5e10ff57aa350d3', 0, 'gIA=', 'co5tec39', 1, 0, '', 0, 0, 0, 1, 0, '', 0);
